defs.docs:
This crate provides to an interface into the linux `procfs` filesystem, usually mounted at
 `/proc`.

defs.name: PF_IDLE
defs.docs: I am an IDLE thread

defs.name: PF_EXITING
defs.docs: Getting shut down

defs.name: PF_EXITPIDONE
defs.docs: PI exit done on shut down

defs.name: PF_VCPU
defs.docs: I'm a virtual CPU

defs.name: PF_WQ_WORKER
defs.docs: I'm a workqueue worker

defs.name: PF_FORKNOEXEC
defs.docs: Forked but didn't exec

defs.name: PF_MCE_PROCESS
defs.docs: Process policy on mce errors;

defs.name: PF_SUPERPRIV
defs.docs: Used super-user privileges

defs.name: PF_DUMPCORE
defs.docs: Dumped core

defs.name: PF_SIGNALED
defs.docs: Killed by a signal

defs.name: PF_MEMALLOC
defs.docs: Allocating memory

defs.name: PF_NPROC_EXCEEDED
defs.docs: set_user() noticed that RLIMIT_NPROC was exceeded

defs.name: PF_USED_MATH
defs.docs: If unset the fpu must be initialized before use

defs.name: PF_USED_ASYNC
defs.docs: Used async_schedule*(), used by module init

defs.name: PF_NOFREEZE
defs.docs: This thread should not be frozen

defs.name: PF_FROZEN
defs.docs: Frozen for system suspend

defs.name: PF_MEMALLOC_NOFS
defs.docs: All allocation requests will inherit GFP_NOFS

defs.name: PF_MEMALLOC_NOIO
defs.docs: All allocation requests will inherit GFP_NOIO

defs.name: PF_LESS_THROTTLE
defs.docs: Throttle me less: I clean memory

defs.name: PF_KTHREAD
defs.docs: I am a kernel thread

defs.name: PF_RANDOMIZE
defs.docs: Randomize virtual address space

defs.name: PF_SWAPWRITE
defs.docs: Allowed to write to swap

defs.name: PF_NO_SETAFFINITY
defs.docs: Userland is not allowed to meddle with cpus_allowed

defs.name: PF_MCE_EARLY
defs.docs: Early kill for mce process policy

defs.name: PF_MUTEX_TESTER
defs.docs: Thread belongs to the rt mutex tester

defs.name: PF_FREEZER_SKIP
defs.docs: Freezer should not count it as freezable

defs.name: PF_SUSPEND_TASK
defs.docs: This thread called freeze_processes() and should not be frozen

defs.name: Running
defs.docs: Running (R)

defs.name: Sleeping
defs.docs: Sleeping in an interruptible wait (S)

defs.name: Waiting
defs.docs: Waiting in uninterruptible disk sleep (D)

defs.name: Zombie
defs.docs: Zombie (Z)

defs.name: Stopped
defs.docs: Stopped (on a signal) (T)

defs.name: Tracing
defs.docs: Tracing stop (t) (Linux 2.6.33 onward)

defs.name: Dead
defs.docs: Dead (X)

defs.name: Wakekill
defs.docs: Wakekill (K) (Linux 2.6.33 to 3.13 only)

defs.name: Waking
defs.docs: Waking (W) (Linux 2.6.33 to 3.13 only)

defs.name: Parked
defs.docs: Parked (P) (Linux 3.9 to 3.13 only)

defs.name: ProcState
defs.value: ProcState::{Running, Sleeping, Waiting, Zombie, Stopped, Tracing, Dead, Wakekill, Waking, Parked}
defs.docs: Represents the state of a process.

defs.name: Stat
defs.value: Stat { pid, comm, state, ppid, pgrp, session, tty_nr, tpgid, flags, minflt, cminflt, majflt, cmajflt, utime, stime, cutime, cstime, priority, nice, num_threads, itrealvalue, starttime, vsize, rss, rsslim, startcode, endcode, startstack, kstkesp, kstkeip, signal, blocked, sigignore, sigcatch, wchan, nswap, cnswap, exit_signal, processor, rt_priority, policy, delayacct_blkio_ticks, guest_time, cguest_time, start_data, end_data, start_brk, arg_start, arg_end, env_start, env_end, exit_code }
defs.docs: Status information about the process, based on the `/proc/<pid>/stat` file.

defs.name: pid
defs.docs: The process ID.

defs.name: comm
defs.docs: The filename of the executable, in parentheses.

defs.name: state
defs.docs: Process State.

defs.name: ppid
defs.docs: The PID of the parent of this process.

defs.name: pgrp
defs.docs: The process group ID of the process.

defs.name: session
defs.docs: The session ID of the process.

defs.name: tty_nr
defs.docs: The controlling terminal of the process.

defs.name: tpgid
defs.docs: The ID of the foreground process group of the controlling terminal of the process.

defs.name: flags
defs.docs: The kernel flags  word of the process.

defs.name: minflt
defs.docs:
The number of minor faults the process has made which have not required loading a memory
 page from disk.

defs.name: cminflt
defs.docs: The number of minor faults that the process's waited-for children have made.

defs.name: majflt
defs.docs:
The number of major faults the process has made which have required loading a memory page
 from disk.

defs.name: cmajflt
defs.docs: The number of major faults that the process's waited-for children have made.

defs.name: utime
defs.docs:
Amount of time that this process has been scheduled in user mode, measured in clock ticks
 (divide by [`ticks_per_second()`].

defs.name: stime
defs.docs:
Amount of time that this process has been scheduled in kernel mode, measured in clock ticks
 (divide by [`ticks_per_second()`]).

defs.name: cutime
defs.docs:
Amount  of  time  that  this  process's  waited-for  children  have  been  scheduled  in
 user  mode,  measured  in clock ticks (divide by [`ticks_per_second()`]).

defs.name: cstime
defs.docs:
Amount of time that this process's waited-for  children  have  been  scheduled  in  kernel
 mode,  measured  in  clock  ticks  (divide  by [`ticks_per_second()`]).

defs.name: priority
defs.docs:
For processes running a real-time scheduling policy (policy below; see sched_setscheduler(2)),
 this is the negated scheduling priority, minus one;

defs.name: nice
defs.docs: The nice value (see `setpriority(2)`), a value in the range 19 (low priority) to -20 (high priority).

defs.name: num_threads
defs.docs:
Number  of  threads in this process (since Linux 2.6).  Before kernel 2.6, this field was
 hard coded to 0 as a placeholder for an earlier removed field.

defs.name: itrealvalue
defs.docs:
The time in jiffies before the next SIGALRM is sent to the process due to an interval
 timer.

defs.name: starttime
defs.docs: The time the process started after system boot.

defs.name: vsize
defs.docs: Virtual memory size in bytes.

defs.name: rss
defs.docs: Resident Set Size: number of pages the process has in real memory.

defs.name: rsslim
defs.docs:
Current soft limit in bytes on the rss of the process; see the description of RLIMIT_RSS in
 getrlimit(2).

defs.name: startcode
defs.docs: The address above which program text can run.

defs.name: endcode
defs.docs: The address below which program text can run.

defs.name: startstack
defs.docs: The address of the start (i.e., bottom) of the stack.

defs.name: kstkesp
defs.docs:
The current value of ESP (stack pointer), as found in the kernel stack page for the
 process.

defs.name: kstkeip
defs.docs: The current EIP (instruction pointer).

defs.name: signal
defs.docs:
The  bitmap of pending signals, displayed as a decimal number.  Obsolete, because it does
 not provide information on real-time signals; use /proc/<pid>/status instead.

defs.name: blocked
defs.docs:
The bitmap of blocked signals, displayed as a decimal number.  Obsolete, because it does
 not provide information on  real-time signals; use /proc/<pid>/status instead.

defs.name: sigignore
defs.docs:
The  bitmap of ignored signals, displayed as a decimal number.  Obsolete, because it does
 not provide information on real-time signals; use /proc/<pid>/status instead.

defs.name: sigcatch
defs.docs:
The bitmap of caught signals, displayed as a decimal number.  Obsolete, because it does not
 provide information  on  real-time signals; use /proc/<pid>/status instead.

defs.name: wchan
defs.docs:
This  is  the  "channel"  in which the process is waiting.  It is the address of a location
 in the kernel where the process is sleeping.  The corresponding symbolic name can be found in
 /proc/<pid>/wchan.

defs.name: nswap
defs.docs: Number of pages swapped **(not maintained)**.

defs.name: cnswap
defs.docs: Cumulative nswap for child processes **(not maintained)**.

defs.name: exit_signal
defs.docs: Signal to be sent to parent when we die.

defs.name: processor
defs.docs: CPU number last executed on.

defs.name: rt_priority
defs.docs: Real-time scheduling priority

defs.name: policy
defs.docs: Scheduling policy (see sched_setscheduler(2)).

defs.name: delayacct_blkio_ticks
defs.docs: Aggregated block I/O delays, measured in clock ticks (centiseconds).

defs.name: guest_time
defs.docs:
Guest time of the process (time spent running a virtual CPU for a guest operating system),
 measured in clock ticks (divide by [`ticks_per_second()`])

defs.name: cguest_time
defs.docs:
Guest time of the process's children, measured in clock ticks (divide by
 [`ticks_per_second()`]).

defs.name: start_data
defs.docs: Address above which program initialized and uninitialized (BSS) data are placed.

defs.name: end_data
defs.docs: Address below which program initialized and uninitialized (BSS) data are placed.

defs.name: start_brk
defs.docs: Address above which program heap can be expanded with brk(2).

defs.name: arg_start
defs.docs: Address above which program command-line arguments (argv) are placed.

defs.name: arg_end
defs.docs: Address below program command-line arguments (argv) are placed.

defs.name: env_start
defs.docs: Address above which program environment is placed.

defs.name: env_end
defs.docs: Address below which program environment is placed.

defs.name: exit_code
defs.docs: The thread's exit status in the form reported by waitpid(2).

defs.name: Io
defs.value: Io { rchar, wchar, syscr, syscw, read_bytes, write_bytes, cancelled_write_bytes }
defs.docs: This struct contains I/O statistics for the process, built from `/proc/<pid>/io`

defs.name: rchar
defs.docs: Characters read

defs.name: wchar
defs.docs: characters written

defs.name: syscr
defs.docs: read syscalls

defs.name: syscw
defs.docs: write syscalls

defs.name: read_bytes
defs.docs: bytes read

defs.name: write_bytes
defs.docs: bytes written

defs.name: cancelled_write_bytes
defs.docs: Cancelled write bytes.

defs.name: MountStat
defs.docs: Mount information from `/proc/<pid>/mountstats`.

defs.name: device
defs.docs: The name of the mounted device

defs.name: mount_point
defs.docs: The mountpoint within the filesystem tree

defs.name: fs
defs.docs: The filesystem type

defs.name: statistics
defs.docs: If the mount is NFS, this will contain various NFS statistics

defs.name: MountNFSStatistics
defs.value: MountNFSStatistics { version, opts, age, caps, sec, events, bytes, per_op_stats }
defs.docs: Only NFS mounts provide additional statistics in `MountStat` entries.

defs.name: version
defs.docs: The version of the NFS statistics block.  Either "1.0" or "1.1".

defs.name: opts
defs.docs: The mount options.

defs.name: age
defs.docs: Duration the NFS mount has been in existence.

defs.name: caps
defs.docs: NFS Capabilities.

defs.name: server_caps
defs.docs: Attempts to parse the caps= value from the [caps] field.

defs.name: NFSEventCounter
defs.docs: Represents NFS data from `/proc/<pid>/mountstats` under the section `events`.

defs.name: NFSByteCounter
defs.value: NFSByteCounter { normal_read, normal_write, direct_read, direct_write, server_read, server_write, pages_read, pages_write }
defs.docs: Represents NFS data from `/proc/<pid>/mountstats` under the section `bytes`.

defs.name: NFSOperationStat
defs.value: NFSOperationStat { operations, transmissions, major_timeouts, bytes_sent, bytes_recv, cum_queue_time, cum_resp_time, cum_total_req_time }
defs.docs: Represents NFS data from `/proc/<pid>/mountstats` under the section of `per-op statistics`.

defs.name: operations
defs.docs: Count of rpc operations.

defs.name: transmissions
defs.docs: Count of rpc transmissions

defs.name: major_timeouts
defs.docs: Count of rpc major timeouts

defs.name: bytes_sent
defs.docs: Count of bytes send. Does not only include the RPC payload but the RPC headers as well.

defs.name: bytes_recv
defs.docs: Count of bytes received as `bytes_sent`.

defs.name: cum_queue_time
defs.docs: How long all requests have spend in the queue before being send.

defs.name: cum_resp_time
defs.docs: How long it took to get a response back.

defs.name: cum_total_req_time
defs.docs:
How long all requests have taken from beeing queued to the point they where completely
 handled.

defs.name: Path
defs.docs: The file that is backing the mapping.

defs.name: Heap
defs.docs: The process's heap.

defs.name: Stack
defs.docs: The initial process's (also known as the main thread's) stack.

defs.name: TStack
defs.docs:
A thread's stack (where the <tid> is a thread ID).  It corresponds to the
 /proc/<pid>/task/<tid>/ path.

defs.name: Vdso
defs.docs: The virtual dynamically linked shared object.

defs.name: Anonymous
defs.docs: An anonymous mapping as obtained via mmap(2).

defs.name: Other
defs.docs: Some other pseudo-path

defs.name: MMapPath
defs.value: MMapPath::{Path, Heap, Stack, TStack, Vdso, Anonymous, Other}

defs.name: MemoryMap
defs.value: MemoryMap { address, perms, offset, dev, inode, pathname }
defs.docs: Represents an entry in a `/proc/<pid>/maps` file.

defs.name: address
defs.docs: The address space in the process that the mapping occupies.

defs.name: offset
defs.docs: The offset into the file/whatever

defs.name: dev
defs.docs: The device (major, minor)

defs.name: inode
defs.docs: The inode on that device

defs.name: Path
defs.docs: A file or device

defs.name: Socket
defs.docs: A socket type, with an inode

defs.name: AnonInode
defs.docs: A file descriptor that have no corresponding inode.

defs.name: MemFD
defs.docs: A memfd file descriptor with a name.

defs.name: Other
defs.docs: Some other file descriptor type, with an inode.

defs.name: FDTarget
defs.value: FDTarget::{Path, Socket, Net, Pipe, AnonInode, MemFD, Other}

defs.name: rss_bytes
defs.docs: Gets the Resident Set Size (in bytes)

defs.name: Process
defs.docs: Represents a process in `/proc/<pid>`.

defs.name: stat
defs.docs: Process status, based on the `/proc/<pid>/stat` file.

defs.name: owner
defs.docs: The user id of the owner of this process

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Tries to create a `Process` based on a PID.

defs.name: myself
defs.docs: Returns a `Process` for the currently running process.

defs.name: cmdline
defs.docs: Returns the complete command line for the process, unless the process is a zombie.

defs.name: pid
defs.docs: Returns the process ID for this process.

defs.name: is_alive
defs.docs: Is this process still alive?

defs.name: cwd
defs.docs:
The the current working directory of the process.  This done by dereferencing the
 `/proc/pid/cwd` symbolic link.

defs.name: environ
defs.docs:
Gets the current environment for the process.  This is done by reading the
 `/proc/pid/environ` file.

defs.name: exe
defs.docs:
The actual path of the executed command, taken by resolving the `/proc/pid/exe` symbolic
 link.

defs.name: io
defs.docs: Return the Io stats for this process, based on the `/proc/pid/io` file.

defs.name: maps
defs.docs:
Return a list of the currently mapped memory regions and their access permissions, based on
 the `/proc/pid/maps` file.

defs.name: fd
defs.docs: Gets a list of open file descriptors for a process

defs.name: coredump_filter
defs.docs: Lists which memory segments are written to the core dump in the event that a core dump is performed.

defs.name: autogroup
defs.docs: Gets the process's autogroup membership

defs.name: auxv
defs.docs: Get the process's auxiliary vector

defs.name: mountstats
defs.docs: Returns the [MountStat] data for this processes mount namespace.

defs.name: Meminfo
defs.value: Meminfo { mem_total, mem_free, mem_available, buffers, cached, swap_cached, active, inactive, active_anon, inactive_anon, active_file, inactive_file, unevictable, mlocked, high_total, high_free, low_total, low_free, mmap_copy, swap_total, swap_free, dirty, writeback, anon_pages, mapped, shmem, slab, s_reclaimable, s_unreclaim, kernel_stack, page_tables, quicklists, nfs_unstable, bounce, writeback_tmp, commit_limit, committed_as, vmalloc_total, vmalloc_used, vmalloc_chunk, hardware_corrupted, anon_hugepages, shmem_hugepages, shmem_pmd_mapped, cma_total, cma_free, hugepages_total, hugepages_free, hugepages_rsvd, hugepages_surp, hugepagesize, direct_map_4k, direct_map_4M, direct_map_2M, direct_map_1G }
defs.docs:
This  struct  reports  statistics about memory usage on the system, based on
 the `/proc/meminfo` file.

defs.name: mem_total
defs.docs: Total usable RAM (i.e., physical RAM minus a few reserved bits and the kernel binary code).

defs.name: mem_free
defs.docs: The sum of [LowFree](#structfield.low_free) + [HighFree](#structfield.high_free).

defs.name: mem_available
defs.docs: An estimate of how much memory is available for starting new applications, without swapping.

defs.name: buffers
defs.docs: Relatively temporary storage for raw disk blocks that shouldn't get tremendously large (20MB or so).

defs.name: cached
defs.docs: In-memory cache for files read from the disk (the page cache).  Doesn't include SwapCached.

defs.name: swap_cached
defs.docs:
Memory  that  once  was  swapped  out, is swapped back in but still also is in the swap
 file.

defs.name: active
defs.docs:
Memory that has been used more recently and usually not reclaimed unless absolutely
 necessary.

defs.name: inactive
defs.docs:
Memory which has been less recently used.  It is more eligible to be reclaimed for other
 purposes.

defs.name: active_anon
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: inactive_anon
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: active_file
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: inactive_file
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: unevictable
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: mlocked
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: high_total
defs.docs: Total amount of highmem.

defs.name: high_free
defs.docs: Amount of free highmem.

defs.name: low_total
defs.docs: Total amount of lowmem.

defs.name: low_free
defs.docs: Amount of free lowmem.

defs.name: mmap_copy
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: swap_total
defs.docs: Total amount of swap space available.

defs.name: swap_free
defs.docs: Amount of swap space that is currently unused.

defs.name: dirty
defs.docs: Memory which is waiting to get written back to the disk.

defs.name: writeback
defs.docs: Memory which is actively being written back to the disk.

defs.name: anon_pages
defs.docs: Non-file backed pages mapped into user-space page tables.

defs.name: mapped
defs.docs: Files which have been mapped into memory (with mmap(2)), such as libraries.

defs.name: shmem
defs.docs: Amount of memory consumed in tmpfs(5) filesystems.

defs.name: slab
defs.docs: In-kernel data structures cache.

defs.name: s_reclaimable
defs.docs: Part of Slab, that cannot be reclaimed on memory pressure.

defs.name: s_unreclaim
defs.docs: Part of Slab, that cannot be reclaimed on memory pressure.

defs.name: kernel_stack
defs.docs: Amount of memory allocated to kernel stacks.

defs.name: page_tables
defs.docs: Amount of memory dedicated to the lowest level of page tables.

defs.name: quicklists
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: nfs_unstable
defs.docs: NFS pages sent to the server, but not yet committed to stable storage.

defs.name: bounce
defs.docs: Memory used for block device "bounce buffers".

defs.name: writeback_tmp
defs.docs: Memory used by FUSE for temporary writeback buffers.

defs.name: commit_limit
defs.docs:
This is the total amount of memory currently available to be allocated on the system,
 expressed  in bytes.

defs.name: committed_as
defs.docs: The  amount of memory presently allocated on the system.

defs.name: vmalloc_total
defs.docs: Total size of vmalloc memory area.

defs.name: vmalloc_used
defs.docs: Amount of vmalloc area which is used.

defs.name: vmalloc_chunk
defs.docs: Largest contiguous block of vmalloc area which is free.

defs.name: hardware_corrupted
defs.docs: [To be documented.]

defs.name: anon_hugepages
defs.docs: Non-file backed huge pages mapped into user-space page tables.

defs.name: shmem_hugepages
defs.docs: Memory used by shared memory (shmem) and tmpfs(5) allocated with huge pages

defs.name: shmem_pmd_mapped
defs.docs: Shared memory mapped into user space with huge pages.

defs.name: cma_total
defs.docs: Total CMA (Contiguous Memory Allocator) pages.

defs.name: cma_free
defs.docs: Free CMA (Contiguous Memory Allocator) pages.

defs.name: hugepages_total
defs.docs: The size of the pool of huge pages.

defs.name: hugepages_free
defs.docs: The number of huge pages in the pool that are not yet allocated.

defs.name: hugepages_rsvd
defs.docs:
This is the number of huge pages for which a commitment to allocate from the pool has been
 made, but no allocation has yet been made.

defs.name: hugepages_surp
defs.docs: This is the number of huge pages in the pool above the value in /proc/sys/vm/nr_hugepages.

defs.name: hugepagesize
defs.docs: The size of huge pages.

defs.name: direct_map_4k
defs.docs: Number of bytes of RAM linearly mapped by kernel in 4kB pages.  (x86.)

defs.name: direct_map_4M
defs.docs: Number of bytes of RAM linearly mapped by kernel in 4MB pages.

defs.name: direct_map_2M
defs.docs: Number of bytes of RAM linearly mapped by kernel in 2MB pages.

defs.name: direct_map_1G
defs.docs: (x86 with CONFIG_X86_64 and CONFIG_X86_DIRECT_GBPAGES enabled.  Since Linux 2.6.27)

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Reads and parses the `/proc/meminfo`, returning `None` if there are problems.

defs.name: TcpState
defs.value: TcpState::{Established, SynSent, SynRecv, FinWait1, FinWait2, TimeWait, Close, CloseWait, LastAck, Listen, Closing, NewSynRecv}

defs.name: TcpNetEntry
defs.value: TcpNetEntry { local_address, remote_address, state, rx_queue, tx_queue, inode }
defs.docs: An entry in the TCP socket table

defs.name: tcp
defs.docs: Reads the tcp socket table

defs.name: tcp6
defs.docs: Reads the tcp6 socket table

defs.name: CpuInfo
defs.docs: Represents the data from `/proc/cpuinfo`.

defs.name: fields
defs.docs: This stores fields that are common among all CPUs

defs.name: num_cores
defs.docs: Get the total number of cpu cores.

defs.name: get_info
defs.docs: Get info for a specific cpu.

defs.name: name
defs.docs: The name of the controller.

defs.name: hierarchy
defs.docs: The  unique  ID  of  the  cgroup hierarchy on which this controller is mounted.

defs.name: num_cgroups
defs.docs: The number of control groups in this hierarchy using this controller.

defs.name: enabled
defs.docs: This field contains the value `true` if this controller is enabled, or `false` if it has been disabled

defs.name: cgroups
defs.docs: Information about the cgroup controllers that are compiled into the kernel

defs.name: hierarchy
defs.docs:
For cgroups version 1 hierarchies, this field contains a  unique  hierarchy  ID  number
 that  can  be  matched  to  a  hierarchy  ID  in /proc/cgroups.  For the cgroups version 2
 hierarchy, this field contains the value 0.

defs.name: controllers
defs.docs:
For cgroups version 1 hierarchies, this field contains a comma-separated list of the
 controllers bound to the hierarchy.

defs.name: pathname
defs.docs:
This field contains the pathname of the control group in the hierarchy to which the process
 belongs.

defs.name: cgroups
defs.docs: Describes control groups to which the process with the corresponding PID belongs.

defs.name: sys
defs.docs:
Sysctl is a means of configuring certain aspects of the kernel at run-time,
 and the `/proc/sys/` directory is there so that you don't even need special tools to do it!

defs.name: kernel
defs.docs: Global kernel info / tuning miscellaneous stuff

defs.name: Version
defs.docs: Represents a kernel version, in major.minor.release version.
